The accepted answer is is correct. However, it&#39;s worth pointing out that if you are implementing password validation, you shouldn&#39;t use Arrays.equals().  Instead, you should use a constant time comparison function that protects against timing attacks.  

I lifted the following code from somewhere in the BouncyCastle sources, iirr, and has passed a couple different rounds of fuzz testing.

```
/**
 * Compare every byte so validation time is constant and, thus,
 * protect against timing attacks.
 */
public static boolean equalsHash( byte[] expected, byte[] presented )
{
    boolean all = false;
    if ( null != expected &amp;&amp; null != presented &amp;&amp; 
         expected.length == presented.length ) {
        all = true;
        for ( int ix = 0; ix &lt; expected.length; ++ix ) {
            boolean same = expected[ix] == presented[ix];
            if ( !same ) {
                all = false;
            }
        }
    }
    return all;
}

